definition.value: A data item that is an aggregate of other data items of the same type that have something in common. Averages and distributions can be determined for data sets.
A textual entity intended to identify a particular publication.
A document that is the output of a publishing process.
Revisit the term in Octorber 2020. Improve the defintion.
A publication that is about an investigation

A data set that is an aggregate of data recording some measurement at a number of time points. The time series data set is an ordered list of pairs of time measurement data and the corresponding measurement data acquired at that time.
a "lethal dose" represents a dose (usually recorded as dose per kilogram of subject body weight) at which a given percentage of subjects will die.
A procedure that can determine the DNA sequence for nearly the entire genome of an individual.
The transfer of a tumor fragment from a patient into an immunodeficient mouse.
A study of the effect of dose changes on the efficacy of a drug in order to determine the dose-response relationship and optimal dose of a therapy.

The determination of the strength of a material, as measured by the ability to produce a specific response. The potency of a pharmacologic substance is measured by the amount needed to produce a certain effect.

The study of the structure of the cells and their arrangement to constitute tissues and, finally, the association among these to form organs.  In pathology, the microscopic process of identifying normal and abnormal morphologic characteristics in tissues, by employing various cytochemical and immunocytochemical stains.
Production of genetic alterations by any technique, including chemicals, radiation, recombination, or other molecular biology methods.
Cardiovascular Pharmacology; the study of the effects of drugs upon the heart or circulatory system

Autoradiographic analysis performed in accordance with specified guidelines that will result in a defined correspondence between the intensity of the autoradiographic image and the amount of radioactivity present in the sample.  This permits assignment of a value to the amount of radioactive material in the object under study.
Models of human disease produced through gene knockout methods
The science concerned with drugs and their actions and uses in kidney biology and the treatment of kidney disease.

A technology used for preclinical research as an alternative to some animal testing.  Micrometer-thin slices of various organs are incubated with various experimental compounds for assays involving toxicology, absorption, distribution, and metabolism.
An in vitro assay in which cultured cells are monitored and analyzed for their ability to move into an acellular area of a culture material.

An experimental system in which (usually) human tumor cells are transplanted into immunocompromised mice that do not reject human cells; cells may be implanted under the skin or into the organ type in which the tumor originated. These model systems may be used for drug development and studies of molecular biological mechanisms of cancer.
The strength of noncovalent chemical binding between two substances as measured by the dissociation constant of the complex.
The amount of time it take for a cessation of bleeding. It is a measurement of the ability of capillaries and platelets to interact to form a blood clot.
The branch of pharmacology that deals with the central nervous system.
The branch of pharmacology that deals with the respiratory system.

a pathological bodily process that occurs after a medical intervention. An adverse event is likely caused by the medical intervention; however, such a causal association is not required to be an adverse event.
The OAE official website is: http://www.oae-ontology.org/.
an adverse event which is a causal adverse event, a pathological bodily process that is induced by a medical intervention.
YH: the term "adverse effect" has the  same meaning of "causal adverse event".
an adverse event that occurs after a vaccination.
an adverse event that occurs after a drug administration
an adverse event that is associated with eating a medical food.
an adverse event that is induced by consuming a nutritional product.
an adverse event that is associated with consuming a dietary supplement.
an adverse event that is associated with consuming an infant formula.
an imaging investigation result abnormal AE that is characterized by an abnormal X-ray
an X-ray result abnormal AE that has an outcome of an abnormality in chest X-ray test
a haematoma AE that has an outcome of contusion.
Contusion is a type of relatively minor hematoma of tissue in which capillaries and sometimes venules are damaged by trauma, allowing blood to seep into the surrounding interstitial tissues.
a digestive system AE which has an outcome of dry throat, which is a sensation of dryness in the throat.
a skin discoloration AE which has an outcome of flushing, a sudden reddening of the face, neck, or upper chest
a pain AE where the pain reachs an extreme level.
a respiratory system AE which has an outcome of postnasal drip, which occurs when excessive mucus is produced by the nasal Mucosa. The excess mucus accumulates in the throat or back of the nose.

a syndrome AE that is subclassified as five defined entities which represent clinical circumstances in which both the heart and the kidney are involved in a bidirectional injury and dysfunction via a final common pathway of cell-to-cell death and accelerated apoptosis mediated by oxidative stress. Types 1 and 2 involve acute and chronic cardiovascular disease (CVD) scenarios leading to acute kidney injury or accelerated chronic kidney disease. Types 2 and 3 describe acute and chronic kidney disease leading primarily to heart failure, although it is possible that acute coronary syndromes, stroke, and arrhythmias could be CVD outcomes in these forms of CRS. Finally, CRS type 5 describes a simultaneous insult to both heart and kidneys, such as sepsis, where both organs are injured simultaneously.
A bursal disorder AE that has an outcome of the symptom of bursitis.
an adverse event that has an outcome of abnormal sign in a musculoskeletal or connective tissue.

A musculoskeletal disorder is an injury or disorder of the muscles, nerves, tendons, joints, cartilage, or supporting structures of the upper or lower limbs, neck, or lower back that are caused, precipitated, or exacerbated by sudden exertion or prolonged exposure to physical factors such as repetition, force, vibration, or awkward posture
a musculoskeletal system AE which has an outcome of bursal disorder
a vaccine adverse event that is induced by an influenza vaccine.
an influenza vaccine adverse event that is induced by a killed influenza vaccine (KIV).
A KIV-induced AE that results in a GBS.

There is little evidence to support a causal association between GBS and most vaccines. The evidence for a causal association is strongest for the swine influenza vaccine that was used in 1976-77. Studies of influenza vaccines used in subsequent years, however, have found small or no increased risk of GBS.  
Reference: http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed?term=19388722.
a muscle pain AE that is induced by Afluria influenza vaccine administration

a behavior and neurological AE that has an outcome of fatigue, which is a state of awareness describing a range of afflictions, usually associated with physical and/or mental weakness, though varying from a general state of lethargy to a specific work-induced burning sensation within one's muscles. Physical fatigue is the inability to continue functioning at the level of one's normal abilities.
